# Stream Maker Tier Rules

## Intent
Design Stream usage for current Maker-tier hard limits while preserving good UX and upgrade-ready modularity.

## Hard Limits (Current Plan)
- Chat: 2,000 MAU per month.
- Activity Feeds: 125,000 API calls per month.
- Video: 333,000 participant minutes per month.
- AI Moderation: $100 monthly credits.

These are hard limits and must be treated as non-burstable ceilings in feature design.

## Architecture Rules
- All Stream interactions must go through shared wrappers/adapters in `packages/shared`.
- Never call Stream SDKs directly from feature UI modules.
- Centralize usage metering hooks (MAU, API calls, participant minutes, moderation usage) in shared integration layer.
- Keep Stream capabilities behind feature flags and policy switches for progressive enablement.
- Apply Stream React Native performance guidance defaults for interval tuning and heavy-feature controls.

## Budgeting and Threshold Rules
- Define monthly budgets per capability and reserve headroom for critical chat paths.
- Implement threshold states for each meter:
  - Green: 0–70% budget used.
  - Yellow: 70–85% budget used.
  - Orange: 85–95% budget used.
  - Red: 95–100% budget used.
- At Yellow and above, reduce non-essential traffic (polling frequency, background refresh, non-critical feed enrichment).
- At Orange and above, disable or queue non-critical plugin actions that consume Stream quotas.
- At Red, preserve baseline chat reliability first; non-core features must degrade gracefully.

## UX Degradation Rules
- Always prioritize send/receive/read chat flows over optional enhancements.
- Show clear user messaging when optional features are temporarily limited.
- Prefer temporary deferral/queueing over hard failure where possible.
- Do not expose internal quota details that could reveal security-sensitive operational posture.

## Feature Design Constraints
- New features must include estimated monthly Stream cost impact before implementation.
- Video features must include minute-budget controls (duration caps, participant caps, quality fallback policy).
- Activity Feed usage must be batched and deduplicated; avoid noisy event fan-out.
- AI moderation usage must apply scoped policies and avoid duplicate evaluations.
- For high media/voice/video usage paths, plan native or cloud offloading from initial design.

## Upgrade-Ready Modularity Rules
- Use a provider interface so Stream limits and behavior can be adjusted by config, not rewrites.
- Keep quota thresholds and kill switches in environment/config control, not hard-coded.
- Preserve compatibility for future paid-tier expansion by avoiding assumptions tied to Maker limits.

## Observability and Alerting
- Emit usage metrics and alerts at threshold transitions (70/85/95/100).
- Track feature-level contribution to quota consumption.
- Keep monthly usage dashboards for product and engineering planning.
- Add early instrumentation for end-to-end latency, JS thread load, and memory usage on mobile chat surfaces.

## CI and Release Gates
- Any Stream-consuming feature must include:
  - quota impact notes,
  - fallback UX behavior,
  - feature flag/kill switch,
  - integration tests for degraded-mode behavior.
- Block merge when Stream fallback behavior is not tested.
- For pull requests modifying Stream-related code, require an updated markdown note in `ctf/docs/quota-impact/`.
- Quota impact notes must include these sections:
  - `## Summary`
  - `## Stream Surfaces Affected`
  - `## Estimated Monthly Impact`
  - `## Budget Threshold Risk`
  - `## Fallback and Degradation Plan`
  - `## Observability`
  - `## Validation`

## Prohibited
- Launching Stream-dependent features without budget allocation.
- Allowing optional plugin automations to consume quotas without rate limits.
- Coupling critical authentication or authorization flows to non-critical Stream features.